{"id": "duc04-testb-32:17#51", "contents": "The government's antitrust case against Microsoft was dealt a significant blow in June when an appeals court ruled that the company's browser and operating system could be considered one product. This decision undercut the government's assertion that the two were separate products, bundled together to stifle competition in the browser market. According to Charles Rule, a former senior official in the Justice Department, the appeals-court ruling weakened the government's case, leading them to adopt a \"blunderbuss approach\" of throwing everything they could find into the case."}
